{"type":"message","id":"d9fe0702","parentId":"4fbd9b68","timestamp":"2026-05-10T09:04:58.981Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Planning milestones and skills**\n\nI need to create a plan with milestones. It seems I should check available skills, but the prompt suggests it’s optional. Since there's prior research, I can skip any redundant exploration. I'll focus on crafting a roadmap with three slices for the project. I also need to determine whether progressive planning is enabled. This might involve deciding if I should aim for a complete plan since I have enough details already. I suspect the three slices should cover authentication, the core project, and integration aspects.**Defining milestones and slices**\n\nI need to establish clear boundaries, possibly with three slices for the project. \n\nS01 would focus on backend authentication, including seeded users, project scoping, and the protected login API, along with the chat workspace shell route. S02 could serve as a CLI skeleton, while also addressing milestones that mention various components like web, backend, and registries. \n\nFor S03, I can incorporate full local checks, including the README update. I’m considering whether we need both web and CLI for acceptance.**Planning slice dependencies and outcomes**\n\nFor S03, I'm considering whether to include placeholder email or WhatsApp gateways along with some smoke checks. It's important to ensure that all three slices collectively meet the milestone outcomes at a proof level. I think it’s okay to have three slices, but I need to clarify that S02 depends on S01, and S03 relies on both S01 and S02. I should also create a boundary map to visualize concrete outputs and make sure all requirements are adequately covered.**Evaluating planning strategy**\n\nI need to clarify that I shouldn’t mention manual file writing. I'll consider using gsd_plan_milestone and maybe gsd_plan_slice, especially since I need to think about the number of slices. With more than one slice, I might need to plan all the slices fully, but sketching could work too if it's progressive planning. However, I’m not entirely sure about preferences, so I may need to inspect some variables like gsd_resume or gsd_exec.**Deciding on planning details**\n\nIt might be safer to set sketches for S02 and beyond since they can be refined later. But the tool requires sketchScope and other fields to be blank or provided if they're genuinely known. The roadmap file template in the milestone may expect fully planned slices. I think gsd_plan_milestone can handle sketches, but we'll need to plan slices later. However, since the prompt mentions planning in full detail if preference is off, I’d prefer to go for full slices to ensure completeness.**Clarifying parameters for milestone**\n\nI'm trying to figure out the parameters for `gsd_plan_milestone`, specifically if I should include `successCriteria` and `definitionOfDone`. It seems like \"definitionOfDo\" is a mistake—it's definitely \"definitionOfDone.\" Also, I'm considering a horizontal checklist, but the tool schema doesn’t seem to have a separate field for that. Hmm, I’ll need to look into how to approach that!**Exploring milestone planning**\n\nI’m thinking the milestone plan tool might create a checklist based on its logic when specific fields are mentioned. I could use verification fields to map things like contract, integration, operational, and UAT. However, I realize that a horizontal checklist might have concerns that relate to cross-cutting issues considered during planning. This could mean mapping them to `verificationOperational` or `requirementCoverage`, but I’m not entirely sure. There's definitely a lot to think about here!**Developing UAT Checklist**\n\nI’m thinking about creating a UAT plan focusing on either manual or scripted local walkthroughs for login, project management, and chat functionality across web and CLI. I might include verification of necessary strings for contract, integration, operational, and UAT processes. A definition of done could include: successful login and project selection, enforcement of server-side checks for permissions and isolation, and ensuring CLI interaction works. I’ll also include smoke checks for user verification and mention the end-to-end paths involved.**Establishing Milestone Success Criteria**\n\nI’m considering a milestone success criteria array with around four key points. First, a seeded user should be able to log in, select a project, and access a project-scoped chat workspace through the Web UI. Unauthorized access to protected sections must be denied by the backend. Authenticated users ought to see placeholders for various elements like runtimes and tools. Lastly, the CLI and smoke checks should function independently of production services. I might also include details on integration closure and observability impact.**Planning decisions**\n\nI’m focusing on order and the placeholder policy. Since planning leads to structural decisions, I'll ensure to plan effectively before saving any decisions. The next step is to call on a function to handle the milestone for the plan. This will help keep everything organized and ensure that I'm on the right track with my planning process! I'm excited to see how this all comes together.","thinkingSignature":"think-tag"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_u0B8u3VrCc7TgCcU8dI2ZgDy","name":"gsd_plan_milestone","arguments":{"actorName":"gsd-orchestrator","boundaryMapMarkdown":"### S01 → S02\n\nProduces:\n- Authenticated session context with `userId`, `projectId`, and `permissions` attached to backend requests and UI state.\n- Project-scoped chat workspace shell and route guards that downstream surfaces can reuse.\n\nConsumes:\n- nothing (first slice)\n\n### S01 → S03\n\nProduces:\n- Seeded local auth flow and project-selection contract that the CLI can reuse.\n- Shared auth/session primitives for non-web entrypoints.\n\nConsumes:\n- nothing (first slice)\n\n### S02 → S03\n\nProduces:\n- Stable registry/listing contracts for models, skills, tools, gateways, and placeholder building-domain surfaces.\n- Placeholder management-page routes that the CLI smoke flow can reference for parity.\n\nConsumes:\n- authenticated session and project context from S01\n","definitionOfDone":["All active M001 requirements are mapped, delivered, deferred, or explicitly out of scope with no orphaned active requirement.","The real local entrypoints exist and are wired together: backend, Web UI, and CLI all start and exercise the same authenticated foundation.","The login → project selection → chat workspace path works through the real Web UI and is protected server-side.","Placeholder runtime/tool/skill/provider/gateway/building-domain surfaces are visible without exposing unauthorized operations or real external integrations.","README and smoke checks explain and verify the local foundation without tribal knowledge."],"dependsOn":[],"keyRisks":[{"risk":"Authentication/session handling may fragment across Web, CLI, and backend boundaries","whyItMatters":"If auth is implemented inconsistently, the primary platform contract becomes unreliable and later slices cannot trust project isolation or permissions."},{"risk":"Placeholder registries and gateways may drift into real integrations too early","whyItMatters":"This milestone must prove safe boundaries, not consume scope on production-grade external systems or building-domain data ingestion."},{"risk":"The foundation may look complete in one client while failing in another","whyItMatters":"The milestone promises a local platform skeleton, so the real proof must cover the assembled system through multiple entrypoints."}],"milestoneId":"M001","proofStrategy":[{"retireIn":"S01","riskOrUnknown":"Authentication/session boundary coherence","whatWillBeProven":"A seeded local user can sign in, select a project, and reach a protected project-scoped chat workspace through the real Web UI while unauthorized access is rejected."},{"retireIn":"S02","riskOrUnknown":"Registry and placeholder boundary drift","whatWillBeProven":"The backend and Web UI can list runtime, tool, skill, provider, gateway, and building-domain placeholder surfaces through permission-checked contracts without enabling real integrations."},{"retireIn":"S03","riskOrUnknown":"Cross-entrypoint runtime coherence","whatWillBeProven":"The CLI can authenticate, select a project, and exercise the same local platform contracts while smoke checks confirm the backend, Web UI, and CLI start together and agree on protected behavior."}],"requirementCoverage":"Mapped to S01: R001, R002, R003, R004. Mapped to S02: R005, R006, R007, R008, R009, R011, R012. Mapped to S03: R010, R013, R014. Deferred intentionally for later milestones: R017, R018. No active requirement is left orphaned.","slices":[{"demo":"After this, a seeded local user can log in through the real Web UI, choose a project, and reach a protected project-scoped chat workspace; unauthorized access is blocked by the backend.","depends":[],"goal":"Ship the authenticated web path with project selection and protected chat workspace.","integrationClosure":"Web UI, backend session handling, and project-scoped authorization all meet at the real login → project → chat path.","isSketch":false,"observabilityImpact":"Emit clear auth/session/project selection events and rejection reasons so access failures can be traced.","proofLevel":"Live end-to-end through the real Web UI and backend, not just fixtures.","risk":"Highest-risk boundary: auth, session shape, and project isolation must be correct before any other surface can trust them.","sketchScope":"","sliceId":"S01","successCriteria":"- Seeded credentials authenticate successfully through the Web UI.\n- Project selection persists into a protected chat workspace route.\n- Direct access to protected routes without a valid session is rejected.\n- Backend request context carries the authenticated user and project scope.","title":"Authenticated web foundation and project-scoped chat"},{"demo":"After this, an authenticated user can inspect real placeholder pages and backend listings for runtime providers, skills, tools, gateways, and building-domain capabilities without exposing real external integrations.","depends":["S01"],"goal":"Add shared registries and placeholder management surfaces for the platform skeleton.","integrationClosure":"Backend registry contracts, permission-checked tool dispatch, placeholder gateways, and navigable Web UI management pages share one stable shape.","isSketch":false,"observabilityImpact":"Log registry reads, permission checks, and placeholder gateway access so boundary violations are visible.","proofLevel":"Live through the real authenticated shell and listing surfaces; placeholders remain intentionally non-operational.","risk":"Placeholder boundaries can easily drift into accidental real integrations or undocumented privilege paths.","sketchScope":"","sliceId":"S02","successCriteria":"- Runtime/provider/tool/skill listings are visible to authenticated users only.\n- Placeholder email and WhatsApp gateways require authentication and do not permit anonymous interaction.\n- Building-domain placeholder tools and skills are registered but clearly non-operational.\n- Web navigation reaches the planned placeholder management pages from the authenticated shell.","title":"Registry skeletons, placeholder gateways, and management pages"},{"demo":"After this, the CLI can authenticate, select a project, and exercise the same local platform contracts; startup smoke checks confirm the backend, Web UI, and CLI all run coherently.","depends":["S01","S02"],"goal":"Deliver the authenticated CLI skeleton and local smoke verification path.","integrationClosure":"The CLI reuses the same auth/session/project contracts and registry listings as the Web UI, proving the foundation is not Web-only.","isSketch":false,"observabilityImpact":"Record CLI auth/project selection/listing commands and smoke-check outcomes for restart and failure diagnosis.","proofLevel":"Live through the real CLI plus smoke checks against the assembled local stack.","risk":"Multi-entrypoint coherence is the last major proof that the skeleton is truly platform-wide instead of only a web demo.","sketchScope":"","sliceId":"S03","successCriteria":"- CLI login, project list, project use, chat, model list, skill list, and tool list commands work with seeded auth.\n- The CLI rejects protected commands when unauthenticated.\n- A local smoke check starts the stack and verifies the main authenticated flow.\n- README instructions are accurate for the tested startup and smoke path.","title":"Authenticated CLI shell and local smoke checks"}],"status":"active","successCriteria":["A seeded user can log in, select a project, and reach a project-scoped chat workspace through the Web UI.","The backend rejects unauthorized access and enforces project-scoped permissions before protected operations run.","Authenticated users can inspect placeholder runtime, tool, skill, provider, gateway, and building-domain surfaces without real external integrations.","The CLI uses the same authenticated foundation and local smoke checks prove the stack starts coherently.","README instructions match the verified local run and smoke path."],"title":"Local Hermes-Like Foundation Skeleton","triggerReason":"planning lane for M001 after research-handoff; roadmap not previously persisted","verificationContract":"Contract verification will cover seeded authentication, session/project context, permission checks, registry/listing contracts, and CLI command behavior.","verificationIntegration":"Integration verification will exercise the real Web UI, backend, placeholder registry/gateway surfaces, and CLI against the same local stack.","verificationOperational":"Operational verification will confirm the local backend, Web UI, and CLI start cleanly, can be shut down cleanly, and can be re-run without manual repair. Horizontal checklist considered during planning: active requirements re-read, prior decisions re-evaluated, graceful shutdown/cleanup, revenue/billing path N/A, auth boundary documented, shared resource budget for local services acceptable, and reconnection/retry strategy for external dependencies is N/A because v1 uses local placeholders only.","verificationUat":"UAT will be a human-checkable walkthrough of login → project selection → chat on the Web UI plus the analogous authenticated CLI flow and placeholder listings.","vision":"Build the smallest authenticated local platform skeleton that proves the BuildingAgent foundation: backend, Web UI, CLI, login, project selection, project-scoped chat, Hermes-inspired runtime/tool/skill/provider seams, placeholder gateways, placeholder building-domain surfaces, and local smoke checks all work coherently."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-openai","model":"gpt-5.5","usage":{"input":8942,"output":8108,"cacheRead":27648,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":44698,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778403806569}}
